pton Montagu, Somerset, England":"Somerset, England"},"en":{"1195–":"1195–Deceased","1194–Male":"1194–Deceased","1212–1260":"1212–1260","1195–Female":"1195–Deceased","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1212":"1212","1195":"1195","1260":"1260","1194":"1194","Sutton Montis, Somerset, England":"Sutton Montis, Somerset, England","Shepton Montagu, Somerset, England":"Somerset, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Ritter","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: from Middle High German <i>rit(t)er</i> ‘knight, mounted warrior’, Middle Low German <i>ridder</i>, applied as a status name, occupational name, or nickname. Compare   Knight  .","English (Middlesex): perhaps a nickname from an agent derivative of Middle English <i>ritten</i> ‘to cut open, split’, usually referring to the use of a blade. Compare   Render  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ridder","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hans, Kurt, Manfred, Otto.","North German: variant of   Ritter   ‘knight, mounted warrior’, a cognate of 2 below.","Dutch: from Middle Dutch <i>riddere</i> ‘knight, rider, horseman’, a status name for a mounted warrior or messenger, or a topographic or habitational name referring to a house bearing the sign of a knight. Compare   De Ridder  ."]},{"name":"Ritterbusch","meanings":["German:","Rhenish-Westphalian topographic name from <i>Retten</i>, <i>Redden</i> ‘swamp’ + <i>Busch</i> ‘woods’.","nickname for a highwayman, a compound of   Ritter   ‘knight, mounted soldier’ +   Busch   ‘bush’."]},{"name":"Knight","meanings":["English: status or occupational name from Middle English <i>knight</i> ‘retainer, attendant’ (Old English <i>cniht</i> ‘boy, youth, lad)’. The specialized feudal sense ‘a high-ranking tenant bound to serve his lord as a mounted soldier’ is not known to have ever given rise to the surname, although it is not out of the question that it may occasionally have been used as a nickname, perhaps for someone who played the part of an armed knight in a local pageant.","Irish: sometimes adopted for Gaelic <b>Mac an Ridire</b> ‘son of the knight’. See also   McKnight  ."]}]},{"name":"Eve","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["vernacular form of the name borne in the Bible by the first woman, created from one of Adam's ribs (Genesis 2:22). It derives, via Latin <i>Eva</i>, from Hebrew <i>Havva</i>, which is considered to be a variant of the vocabulary word <i>hayya</i> ‘living’ or ‘animal’. Adam gave names to all the animals (Genesis 2:19–20) and then to his wife, who was ‘the mother of all living’ (Genesis 3:20)."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":20,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705188,"age":29,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705189,"age":64,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Eve Ritter was born in 1195, in Somerset, England. She h